sections.content:
## Data Migrations

When your model schema changes (new properties, renamed fields, changed types), SwiftData needs a migration plan to transform existing data.

### Lightweight (Automatic) Migrations

Simple changes like adding a new property with a default value are handled automatically:

```swift
@Model
class Book {
    var title: String
    var pageCount: Int
    var rating: Int = 0  // New property with default — automatic
}
```

### VersionedSchema and SchemaMigrationPlan

For complex changes, define explicit versions and a migration plan:

```swift
enum BookSchemaV1: VersionedSchema {
    static var versionID = Schema.Version(1, 0, 0)
    static var models: [any PersistentModel.Type] { [Book.self] }
    @Model
    class Book {
        var title: String
    }
}

enum BookSchemaV2: VersionedSchema {
    static var versionID = Schema.Version(2, 0, 0)
    static var models: [any PersistentModel.Type] { [Book.self] }
    @Model
    class Book {
        var title: String
        var isbn: String
    }
}
```

Then create a `SchemaMigrationPlan` that defines how to move between versions:

```swift
enum BookMigrationPlan: SchemaMigrationPlan {
    static var schemas: [any VersionedSchema.Type] { [BookSchemaV1.self, BookSchemaV2.self] }
    static var stages: [MigrationStage] {
        [MigrationStage.custom(
            fromVersion: BookSchemaV1.self,
            toVersion: BookSchemaV2.self,
            willMigrate: { context in
                // Assign default ISBN to existing books
            }
        )]
    }
}
```

Pass the migration plan to your container: `ModelContainer(for: Book.self, migrationPlan: BookMigrationPlan.self)`.

